---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import RelatedLinks from '../components/RelatedLinks.astro';

/*
  CERTIFICATE OF DATA DESTRUCTION article. COPY verbatim from
  content/articles/proofwipe-certificate-of-destruction.md (owner voice, no em
  dashes). Layout + SEO only. Links: proofwipe.com/verify to /verify, closing
  proofwipe.com to /download, and "our guide to how ProofWipe wipes a drive and
  proves it" to /how-it-works. Keep the {' '} before inline links, since Astro
  collapses newline-only whitespace.
*/

const titleTag = 'What a Certificate of Data Destruction Should Show | ProofWipe';
const description =
  'A real certificate of data destruction names the drive and serial, the method, the verification result, the date, and carries a tamper-evident fingerprint. Here is how to tell a strong one from a template.';

const jsonLd = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@graph': [
    {
      '@type': 'Article',
      headline: 'What a certificate of data destruction should show',
      description,
      author: { '@type': 'Organization', name: 'ProofWipe' },
      publisher: { '@type': 'Organization', name: 'ProofWipe', url: 'https://proofwipe.com' },
      mainEntityOfPage: 'https://proofwipe.com/certificate-of-data-destruction',
    },
    {
      '@type': 'FAQPage',
      mainEntity: [
        {
          '@type': 'Question',
          name: 'What should a certificate of data destruction include?',
          acceptedAnswer: {
            '@type': 'Answer',
            text: 'At a minimum: the exact drive make/model and serial number, the sanitization method and standard used, the verification result, the date and time, and a tamper-evident fingerprint so it cannot be altered without detection.',
          },
        },
        {
          '@type': 'Question',
          name: 'Is a typed certificate template good enough?',
          acceptedAnswer: {
            '@type': 'Answer',
            text: 'No. A template filled in by hand proves nothing, because the details could be wrong or changed and nobody can check them. A real certificate is generated by the tool that did the wipe and can be independently verified.',
          },
        },
        {
          '@type': 'Question',
          name: 'How can someone confirm a ProofWipe certificate is genuine?',
          acceptedAnswer: {
            '@type': 'Answer',
            text: 'They paste it at proofwipe.com/verify, which recomputes its fingerprint in the browser and confirms it matches the record, with nothing uploaded.',
          },
        },
      ],
    },
  ],
};
---

<BaseLayout
  titleTag={titleTag}
  title="Certificate of data destruction"
  description={description}
  jsonLd={jsonLd}
  ogType="article"
  ogImage="/og/certificate-of-data-destruction.png"
>
  <article class="container-page py-14 lg:py-20">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
      <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-accent">Guide</p>
      <h1 class="mt-2 text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight sm:text-4xl">
        What a certificate of data destruction should show
      </h1>

      <div class="prose-pw mt-8 space-y-5 text-[1.0625rem] leading-relaxed text-muted">
        <p>
          If you dispose of drives for a business, sooner or later someone asks for proof. A client,
          an auditor, a buyer, or your own records. The document that answers them is a certificate
          of data destruction. The trouble is that &ldquo;certificate&rdquo; can mean anything from
          a real, verifiable record to a Word template someone typed a serial number into. Here is
          what a certificate actually needs to show to be worth anything, and how to tell a strong
          one from a weak one.
        </p>

        <h2 class="pt-4 text-2xl font-semibold text-text">Why the certificate matters</h2>
        <p>
          Wiping a drive and being able to prove you wiped it are two different things. The wipe
          protects the data. The certificate protects you. When a client asks how their information
          was disposed of, or an auditor wants to see your process, or a buyer wants assurance the
          machine is clean, &ldquo;we wiped it&rdquo; is not an answer. A certificate is. It is the
          record that turns a private action into something you can stand behind in front of someone
          else.
        </p>

        <h2 class="pt-4 text-2xl font-semibold text-text">What a good certificate includes</h2>
        <p>
          A certificate is only as good as the specific, checkable facts on it. At a minimum it
          should show:
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong class="text-text">The exact drive.</strong> The make, model, and above all the
          serial number of the drive that was wiped. A certificate that does not name the specific
          drive proves nothing about the drive in question. The serial number is what ties the
          record to the physical hardware.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong class="text-text">The method used.</strong> Which sanitization method was applied,
          and to what standard. &ldquo;NIST 800-88 Purge&rdquo; or &ldquo;NIST 800-88 Clear&rdquo;
          tells a reader exactly what was done and lets them judge whether it suits the drive.
          &ldquo;Wiped&rdquo; on its own does not.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong class="text-text">The verification result.</strong> Whether the wipe was checked
          afterward by reading the drive back, and whether it passed. A method without verification
          is a claim. A verified result is evidence the data is actually gone, not just that an
          erase was attempted.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong class="text-text">The date and time.</strong> When the sanitization happened, so
          the record sits in a timeline you can defend.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong class="text-text">A tamper-evident fingerprint.</strong> Some way to confirm the
          certificate has not been altered since it was created. Without this, any certificate is
          just editable text, and a serial number or a date could be changed after the fact with no
          trace.
        </p>

        <h2 class="pt-4 text-2xl font-semibold text-text">The difference between a real certificate and a template</h2>
        <p>
          Plenty of &ldquo;certificates of destruction&rdquo; are just a form. Someone runs a wipe,
          opens a template, and types in the details by hand. Nothing stops those details being
          wrong, whether by mistake or on purpose, and nothing lets a reader confirm them. It looks
          official and proves nothing.
        </p>
        <p>
          A real certificate is generated by the tool that did the wipe, from the actual result of
          that wipe, and it is verifiable. That means the drive details, method, and result are
          recorded by the software as they happened, not typed in afterward, and there is a way for
          anyone holding the certificate to check it is genuine and unaltered. The fingerprint is
          what makes that possible. If the certificate and its underlying log are cryptographically
          tied together, changing either one breaks the match, and the check fails. That is the line
          between a document you hope is trusted and one that can be independently confirmed.
        </p>

        <h2 class="pt-4 text-2xl font-semibold text-text">What ProofWipe produces</h2>
        <p>
          ProofWipe generates a certificate for every drive it sanitizes, straight from the result
          of the wipe. Each one lists the drive and its serial number, the NIST 800-88 method used,
          the read-back verification result, and the date and time. It carries a tamper-evident
          fingerprint, a SHA-256 hash tying the certificate to the wipe's log, so any later change to
          either would be caught.
        </p>
        <p>
          Anyone can verify a certificate at{' '}
          <a href="/verify" class="font-medium text-accent hover:underline">proofwipe.com/verify</a>.
          It recomputes the fingerprint in the browser and confirms it matches, with nothing
          uploaded. So the buyer or auditor you hand it to does not have to take your word or ours.
          They can check it themselves.
        </p>
        <p>
          If you are disposing of drives and need to prove it, that is the standard to hold any
          certificate to: specific, verified, and tamper-evident, not just a printed claim. Get
          ProofWipe at{' '}
          <a href="/download" class="font-medium text-accent hover:underline">proofwipe.com</a>, and
          see how the wipe and verification work in{' '}
          <a href="/how-it-works" class="font-medium text-accent hover:underline"
            >our guide to how ProofWipe wipes a drive and proves it</a>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <RelatedLinks links={['/how-it-works', '/pipeda-data-destruction', '/verify']} />
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
